GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF NORTH CAROLINA
SESSION 2025
H 1
HOUSE BILL 519
Short Title: Parents' Medical Bill of Rights. (Public)
Sponsors: Representatives Balkcom, Loftis, Biggs, and Potts (Primary Sponsors).
For a complete list of sponsors, refer to the North Carolina General Assembly web site.
Referred to: Health, if favorable, Judiciary 2, if favorable, Rules, Calendar, and Operations of
the House
March 27, 2025
1 A BILL TO BE ENTITLED
2 AN ACT REVISING THE LAWS REGARDING WHEN MINORS CAN GIVE EFFECTIVE
3 CONSENT TO MEDICAL TREATMENT ON THEIR OWN AUTHORITY AND WHEN
4 PARENTS ARE ALLOWED ACCESS TO MINORS' MEDICAL RECORDS.
5 The General Assembly of North Carolina enacts:
6 SECTION 1. G.S. 90-21.4 reads as rewritten:
7 "§ 90-21.4. Responsibility, liability and immunity of physicians.
8 (a) Any physician licensed to practice medicine in North Carolina providing health
9 services to a minor under the terms, conditions and circumstances of this Article shall not be held
10 liable in any civil or criminal action for providing such services without having obtained
11 permission from the minor's parent, legal guardian, person standing in loco parentis, or a legal
12 custodian other than a parent when granted specific authority in a custody order to consent to
13 medical or psychiatric treatment. The physician shall not be relieved on the basis of this Article
14 from liability for negligence in the diagnosis and treatment of a minor.
15 (b) The physician shall not notify a parent, legal guardian, person standing in loco
16 parentis, or a legal custodian other than a parent when granted specific authority in a custody
17 order to consent to medical or psychiatric treatment, without the permission of the minor,
18 concerning the medical health services set out in G.S. 90-21.5(a), unless the situation in the
19 opinion of the attending physician indicates that notification is essential to the life or health of
20 the minor. If a parent, legal guardian[,] person standing in loco parentis, or a legal custodian other
21 than a parent when granted specific authority in a custody order to consent to medical or
22 psychiatric treatment contacts the physician concerning the treatment or medical services being
23 provided to the minor, the physician may give information."
24 SECTION 2. G.S. 90-21.5 reads as rewritten:
25 "§ 90-21.5. Minor's consent sufficient for certain medical health services.
26 (a) Subject to subsection (a1) of this section, any Any minor may give effective consent
27 to a physician licensed to practice medicine in North Carolina for medical health services for the
28 prevention, diagnosis and treatment of (i) venereal disease and other diseases reportable under
29 G.S. 130A-135, (ii) pregnancy, (iii) abuse of controlled substances or alcohol, and (iv) emotional
30 disturbance. pregnancy. This section does not authorize the inducing of an abortion, performance
31 of a sterilization operation, or admission to a 24-hour facility licensed under Article 2 of Chapter
32 122C of the General Statutes except as provided in G.S. 122C-223. This section does not prohibit
33 the admission of a minor to a treatment facility upon his own written application in an emergency
34 situation as authorized by G.S. 122C-223.
*H519-v-1*

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (a1) Notwithstanding any other provision of law to the contrary, a health care provider
2 shall obtain written consent from a parent or legal guardian prior to administering any vaccine
3 that has been granted emergency use authorization and is not yet fully approved by the United
4 States Food and Drug Administration to an individual under 18 years of age.
5 (b) Any minor who is emancipated may consent to any medical treatment, dental
6 services, and health services for himself that minor or for his that minor's child."
7 SECTION 3. Article 1A of Chapter 90 of the General Statutes is amended by adding
8 two new sections to read:
9 "§ 90-21.5A. Limited exception for examination without parental consent in cases of
10 suspected abuse or neglect.
11 (a) A health care practitioner may conduct or continue an examination of a minor without
12 first obtaining written or documented consent from a parent if the health care practitioner has a
13 reasonable belief that the examination will reveal information triggering an obligation to report
14 under G.S. 7B-301.
15 (b) A physician may conduct or continue an examination of a minor without first
16 obtaining written or documented consent from a parent if the physician has a reasonable belief
17 that the examination will reveal information triggering an obligation to report under
18 G.S. 90-21.20(c1).
19 "§ 90-21.5B. Parental access to minors' medical records.
20 (a) Parents have the right to access and review all medical records of their minor child,
21 including medical records of care for which the minor may give effective consent under
22 G.S. 90-21.5(a).
23 (b) Notwithstanding subsection (a) of this section, parents do not have the right to access
24 and review the medical records of their minor child if any of the following apply:
25 (1) The medical records are of health care described in G.S. 90-21.5A.
26 (2) The release of the medical records is prohibited by a valid court order.
27 (3) The parent is the subject of an investigation for a crime committed against the
28 minor child and a law enforcement agency or official has requested that the
29 medical records not be released."
30 SECTION 4. This act becomes effective October 1, 2025, and applies to acts
31 occurring on or after that date.
